Very Basic Spatial Econometrics

Joseph Snitzer

Introduction

Econometrics should be spatial, but not spatial econometrics as its been developed. Amine Ouazad

This page is an attempt to explain some essential concepts from the field of spatial econometrics. This field is gaining more focus today, and has moved far beyond where it was in 1988 at the time of Luc Anselins famous publication. However, because it is not a widely taught subject, it felt appropriate to attempt to present some of the basic concepts in an accessible (and visual!) way, since an often ignored part of spatial econometric education is the ability to exploit data visualization1 For instance, concepts like spatial autocorrelation have a spatial and visual basis that makes the concept more intuitive. There is no need to teach spatial econometrics the same way we teach time series econometrics, which is harder to see visually. The key texts we will consult are A Primer in Spatial Econometrics, as well as the two other intro books need to include here.

Motivation

This is mainly a way to explore how to use RMarkdown to make simple explainers for concepts, hopefully aiding in my own understanding of the concepts.

Spatial Weights Matrix

We first will consider the fundamental conceptual tool used in spatial econometrics: the spatial weights matrix. Because we are motivated to use spatial econometric tools because we believe there is a degree of correlation to our data, we will need a way to quantify this degree of relation between spatial units. Whereas temporal lags are an obvious way by which to account for temporal autocorrelation in time series models, there is not as clearcut a way to measure spatial relations.
In the formalized model, well see that there are certain ways to construct a weights matrix that will be more beneficial than others2 For example, we wont consider a spatial unit to be a neighbor to itself, for reasons well explore later.
